==English==
===Spelling Variants===
*''(US, archaic UK)'' - '''[[fulfill]]'''
*''(UK standard)'' - '''[[fulfil]]'''

===Etymology===
Late Old English [[fullfyllan]], corresponding to [[full]] + [[fill]].

===Pronunciation===
*(''UK'') {{IPA|/fʊl'fɪl/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|fulfill|fulfills|fulfilled|fulfilling}}
# ''(archaic)'' to fill up
#:''My lady is positively '''fulfilled''' of grace.''
# To [[satisfy]], carry out, bring to completion (an obligation, a requirement, etc.).
#:''You made a promise, son, and now you must '''fulfill''' it.''
# To emotionally or artistically [[satisfy]]; to develop one's gifts to the fullest
#:''This is the most '''fulfilling''' work I've ever done.''
# To [[obey]], [[follow]], comply with (a rule, requirement etc.)
#:''Unfortunately, you don't '''fulfill''' the criteria for extra grants at the present time.''

====Translations====
'''satisfy, carry out'''
*Spanish: [[satisfacer]], [[cumplir]]

===Derived Terms===
*[[fulfilled]], [[fulfilling]], [[fulfillable]]